l information and constitutes what can be called an "icon" of evolution. Voss shows how Darwin "thought with his eyes" and how his pictorial representations and the development and popularization of the theory of evolution were vitally interconnected. Voss explores four of Darwin's images in depth, and weaves about them a story on the development and presentation of Darwin's theory, in which she also addresses the history of Victorian illustration, the role of images in science, the technologies of production, and the relationship between specimen, words, and images.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Evolution.2bisacsh1 aLantz, Lori08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300163100423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300163100.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles